The erroneous code fails because the variable named variable is declared but never assigned a value before use. Java requires local variables to be initialized before printing.

Here is the corrected main class that assigns the initial value:

```java
public class Main {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        String variable = "Hello world";
        System.out.println(variable);
    }
}
```

The next class assigns a new value to the variable:

```java
public class ValueAssigner {
    public static String assignNewValue(String variable) {
        variable = "New value assigned";
        return variable;
    }
}
```

The following class concatenates the variable with another string:

```java
public class StringConcatenator {
    public static String concatenateValue(String variable) {
        String suffix = " and more";
        variable = variable + suffix;
        return variable;
    }
}
```

The final class compares the variable to another string and returns the result:

```java
public class StringComparator {
    public static boolean compareValue(String variable) {
        String target = "Hello world";
        return variable.equals(target);
    }
}
```
